# Initialization

DOCUMENT();

loadMacros(
"PGstandard.pl",
"MathObjects.pl",
"PGchoicemacros.pl"
);

TEXT(beginproblem());

$radio1 = new_multiple_choice();
$radio1->qa("Do you need to flip over this card?","Yes");
$radio1->extra("No");
$radio1->makeLast("No");

$radio2 = new_multiple_choice();
$radio2->qa("Do you need to flip over this card?","No");
$radio2->extra("Yes");
$radio2->makeLast("No");


############################
# Main Text

Context()->texStrings;
BEGIN_TEXT

Here are four \( (x, y) \) ordered pairs where the \( x\) and \(y\) values are unknown:$BR
 \( (2, y), (6, y), (x, 11), (x, 9) \) $BR
 You want to know if this assertion is true: $BR
 If \(x>5\) then \(y \leq 10\).  
$PAR
To check the assertion, you may need to flip over some cards and look at the  unknown values of \(x\) or \(y\).  Which cards?

$PAR
\{$radio1->print_q()\} $BR 
\( (6, y) \)
\{$radio1->print_a()\} 

$BR 
\{$radio2->print_q()\} $BR 
\( (x, 9) \)
\{$radio2->print_a()\} 

$BR
\{$radio2->print_q()\} $BR 
\( (2, y) \)
\{$radio2->print_a()\} 

$BR
\{$radio1->print_q()\} $BR 
\( (x, 11) \)
\{$radio1->print_a()\} 


END_TEXT
Context()->normalStrings;

############################
# Answer Evaluation

ANS(radio_cmp($radio1->correct_ans()));
ANS(radio_cmp($radio2->correct_ans()));
ANS(radio_cmp($radio2->correct_ans()));
ANS(radio_cmp($radio1->correct_ans()));

$showPartialCorrectAnswers = 1;

Context()->texStrings;
SOLUTION(EV3(<<'END_SOLUTION'));
